04939nam a22008535i 9780520933644DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209336447 a10.1525/97805209336442doi  a(DE-B1597)519838  a(OCoLC)134938527  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0060002bisacsh1 aKramer, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Classical Music Still Matters /cLawrence Kramer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (251 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIn Lieu Of A Preface -- tChapter One. Classical Music And Its Values -- tChapter Two. The Fate Of Melody And The Dream Of Return -- tChapter Three. Score And Performance, Performance And Film: Classical Music As Liberating Energy -- tChapter Four. But Not For Me: Love Song And The Heartache Of Modern Life -- tChapter Five. The Ghost In The Machine: Keyboard Rhapsodies -- tChapter Six. Crisis And Memory: The Music Of Lost Time -- tChapter Seven. Persephone’S Fiddle: The Value Of Classical Music -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"What can be done about the state of classical music?" Lawrence Kramer asks in this elegant, sharply observed, and beautifully written extended essay. Classical music, whose demise has been predicted for at least a decade, has always had its staunch advocates, but in today’s media-saturated world there are real concerns about its viability. Why Classical Music Still Matters takes a forthright approach by engaging both skeptics and music lovers alike. In seven highly original chapters, Why Classical Music Still Matters affirms the value of classical music—defined as a body of nontheatrical music produced since the eighteenth century with the single aim of being listened to—by revealing what its values are: the specific beliefs, attitudes, and meanings that the music has supported in the past and which, Kramer believes, it can support in the future.Why Classical Music Still Matters also clears the air of old prejudices. Unlike other apologists, whose defense of the music often depends on arguments about the corrupting influence of popular culture, Kramer admits that classical music needs a broader, more up-to-date rationale. He succeeds in engaging the reader by putting into words music’s complex relationship with individual human drives and larger social needs. In prose that is fresh, stimulating, and conversational, he explores the nature of subjectivity, the conquest of time and mortality, the harmonization of humanity and technology, the cultivation of attention, and the liberation of human energy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a18th century.  aacademic.  aapologists.  achopin.  aclassical composers.  aclassical music.  aclassical musicians.  acomposers.  agershwin.  ahuman nature.  ajohann sebastian bach.  ajohannes brahms.  alove song.  amedia.  amozart.  amusic lovers.  amusic performance.  amusic studies.  amusical composers.  amusical history.  amusicians.  apiano music.  apopular culture.  aravel.  ascholarly.  aschubert.  aschumann.  atechnology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025082640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093364440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933644/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Pa